ng, not generation quality. MULTI-STEP: We can pre-populate `grounding` without running evaluate, so the full pipeline is not required.","test_description":"Create an in-memory artifact store pre-populated with a `grounding` value. Run the implement-stage command against it with stubbed inputs. Assert: (1) the command reads from `grounding` (not `plan`), and (2) the artifact store's `plan` key is written with implement's output while `grounding` is not overwritten.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Deep-dive no longer overwrites `plan` as a redundant side effect when diagnosis already exists in issue content.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is a conditional branch inside deep-dive: if diagnosis exists, skip the plan write. This is a single-module logic check — no cross-module handoff is required to expose it. REAL-INFRA: No. MOCK-HIDE: We can spy on the artifact store write method; as long as we can observe whether it was called with `plan`, a mock is sufficient and won't hide the failure. LLM-DEP: We are testing a code-level guard (does deep-dive skip the write?), not model output. MULTI-STEP: No.","test_description":"Call deep-dive with a fixture issue object that already contains a non-empty diagnosis in its content. Spy on the artifact store's write method. Assert that write is never called with the `plan` key during this invocation.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.55,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"In a full multi-step agent run (`deep-dive -> write-plan/evaluate -> implement`), the final implementation plan reflects grounding produced earlier in the run.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure only manifests when artifact state written by evaluate is actually present and consumed by implement after deep-dive has run. No single module test or two-module integration test can reproduce a grounding artifact that is stale or absent because an upstream step stomped it. REAL-INFRA: No OS dependency, but the steps must execute in sequence against shared state. LLM-DEP: If the grounding content is LLM-generated and downstream steps branch on it, real LLM calls may be needed; even with stubs the multi-step sequencing is the core failure mode. MULTI-STEP: Yes — explicitly requires three agentic steps in order with shared artifact store.","test_description":"Run the full `deep-dive → evaluate → implement` pipeline against a shared in-memory artifact store (with LLM calls stubbed to return fixture responses). After all steps complete, assert that the `plan` artifact contains a marker/field that traces back to the grounding content written by evaluate — proving that implement consumed the correct artifact rather than a stale or empty slot.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.13,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When grounding is absent, implement falls back safely and still emits a valid plan artifact without corrupting other stored artifacts.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Two failure modes must be checked: (a) implement writes a valid plan, and (b) implement does not corrupt other artifact slots. Failure mode (b) requires the artifact store to have pre-existing entries and be observable after the call — a pure unit test of implement's fallback path cannot check store integrity without wiring the store. REAL-INFRA: No. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the store as a black box would hide corruption; using a real or transparent in-memory store lets us inspect all keys post-run. LLM-DEP: No — we are testing graceful degradation and artifact hygiene. MULTI-STEP: No.","test_description":"Create 